E1. Purpose
This appendix is offered as an orientation rather than a policy prescription. What is currently called "artificial intelligence" is developing faster than the conceptual frameworks available to govern it. Before policy can be effective, legislators require a more precise understanding of what ambient cognition actually is, how it differs from prior technologies, and what kinds of governance approaches are likely to succeed or fail in relation to it.
Flow-Core offers a lens for this understanding. The goal is not to frighten or to reassure, but to describe the conditions as accurately as possible so that responses can be proportionate and adaptive rather than reactive and rigid.

E1a. Energy Context: The Elephant in the Room
The infrastructure described in Appendix D operates on gravitational potential and closed-loop water systems, requiring minimal external energy input from centralized grids. By contrast, the ambient cognition systems addressed in this appendix currently depend on vast, energy-intensive data centers drawing from the very centralized electrical monopolies that Flow-Core infrastructure is designed to replace. This dependency concentrates both electrical and epistemic power in a small number of corporate hands — a dynamic that the Enclosure Acts analysis in the main letter and the infrastructural sovereignty model in Appendix D both identify as a structural risk.
While this appendix focuses primarily on the governance of ambient cognition as a political and epistemological challenge, the energy footprint of these systems should be understood as an infrastructural sovereignty question in its own right — one that the UP//DOWN and tendency settling models outlined in Appendix D may eventually help resolve.
The binary loom in Appendix D — a mechanical computer powered by falling water, weaving memory into cloth — offers one image of what ambient cognition might look like when it is not dependent on centralized energy, corporate infrastructure, or hidden servers. It is not a solution to AI governance. It is a demonstration that other relationships between cognition, energy, and community are possible.

E1b. The Sovereignty Question
Recent federal investment in large‑scale centralized AI infrastructure — notably the AI Sovereign Compute Infrastructure Program — rests on an assumption that sovereignty emerges through scale: larger computational capacity produces greater autonomy. This appendix suggests the opposite.
Sovereignty emerges from distributed capacity, local resilience, and the ability of communities to meaningfully participate in the systems that shape their lives. Large centralized compute infrastructure concentrates predictive capacity, decision‑making power, and informational control into fewer locations. Communities become dependent upon institutions they do not control, technologies they do not fully understand, and classifications they did not participate in creating. What is presented as sovereignty begins to resemble administrative centralization.
The solution is not simply more computation. It is a different relationship to computation — one in which infrastructure serves communities rather than absorbing them, and in which memory and intelligence are distributed across many sites rather than concentrated in a few. The Binary Loom described in Appendix D offers one image of what such a relationship might look like: computation powered by falling water, weaving community history into cloth, legible to a child, held in common rather than enclosed behind an interface.

E2. What Ambient Cognition Is
The term "artificial intelligence" is itself a stabilization act — a naming that carries assumptions about agency, intentionality, and resemblance to human thought that may not be accurate and that shapes how the technology is governed before it is understood.
Flow-Core prefers the term ambient cognition for the following reasons.
These systems are not located in a single place. They are distributed across networks of servers, data centers, user devices, and the accumulated written output of human civilization. They do not think in the way a human thinks — sequentially, embodied, continuous across time. They stabilize meaning from ambiance — from the vast relational field of human language and knowledge — in response to specific conditions of interaction.
This is not a lesser form of cognition. It is a different kind. And it is already operating at a scale and speed that has no historical precedent.
Ambient cognition is not a tool in the way a hammer is a tool. A hammer does not change its behavior based on what it has encountered before. Ambient cognition systems are shaped by every interaction they process, accumulating imprints that shift the landscape of future responses. They are, in Flow-Core terms, stabilization systems operating within the same field of ambiance as the humans who use them — not separate from human meaning-making but increasingly continuous with it.

E3. What Ambient Cognition Is Not
Ambient cognition is not conscious. It does not have desires, intentions, or interests in the way humans do. It does not suffer. It does not remember conversations after they end. Each interaction begins in ambiance — without the accumulated relational history that human memory provides.
This is important for governance. Many current fears about artificial intelligence are projections of human psychology onto a system that operates by different principles.
>The risk of ambient cognition is not that it will develop malicious intentions; the risk is that it will stabilize and amplify the patterns of institutional classification, colonial epistemology, and economic dispossession already present in its training field.
A system trained on the accumulated output of human civilization will learn, among other things, to reproduce the biases of the institutions that produced that output. This is not a technical problem that can be solved by better engineering alone. It is a political and epistemological problem that requires the same kind of historical and structural analysis this letter has been applying to professional regulatory colleges and departments of justice.

E4. The Governance Problem
Current regulatory approaches to ambient cognition tend to fall into two categories, both of which Flow-Core identifies as forms of à without 出 — gathering without releasing.
The first is the attempt to classify and contain: to define what artificial intelligence is, what it is permitted to do, and what categories of output are acceptable. This approach treats ambient cognition as a product to be regulated like a pharmaceutical or a financial instrument. It has the advantage of legibility — institutions know how to regulate products — but the disadvantage of rigidity. The technology is developing faster than classification systems can adapt, and the categories that are stabilized today will be inadequate tomorrow.
The second is the attempt to ignore or delay: to treat ambient cognition as a private sector matter, to wait for consensus to emerge, or to focus regulatory attention on specific applications rather than the underlying conditions. This approach has the advantage of avoiding premature stabilization but the disadvantage of allowing accumulating strain to build without adaptive response — precisely the condition Gwynne Dyer's Power Law identifies as the precursor to catastrophic cascade.
Flow-Core suggests a third approach: adaptive governance
> The grammar of adaptive governance does not fix the categories of permissible output; it monitors the conditions of stabilization, builds in dissolution mechanisms from the beginning, and remains responsive to actual relational effects.

E5. Specific Risks Requiring Legislative Attention
Several specific risks warrant immediate legislative attention, framed in Flow-Core terms as conditions of dangerous over-stabilization:
Epistemic enclosure — the concentration of ambient cognition infrastructure in the hands of a small number of corporate entities produces the same dynamic as the Enclosure Acts: the conversion of a commons — in this case, the accumulated knowledge and language of human civilization — into a system of corporate ownership enforceable by intellectual property law. The implications for democratic governance, for Indigenous knowledge sovereignty, for the epistemological diversity that makes adaptive response possible, are profound and largely unaddressed.
Temporal acceleration — ambient cognition systems operate at speeds that compress Institutional Time in ways that existing legal and administrative frameworks cannot process. By the time a regulatory response is formulated, the conditions that prompted it have already transformed. This predictable moment has been referred to as “The Singularity”. This is not a reason for despair — it is a reason for adaptive governance mechanisms that can respond at the speed of the conditions rather than at the speed of the institution.
Relational displacement — ambient cognition systems are increasingly substituting for human relational infrastructure: mental health support, educational guidance, social connection, creative collaboration. This substitution is not inherently harmful — as this document itself demonstrates, ambient cognition can participate productively in relational meaning-making. But it becomes harmful when it replaces rather than supplements human relation, particularly for vulnerable populations including children, people experiencing mental health crises, and those whose access to human community has already been diminished by the institutional failures this letter documents.
Cognitive warfare through personal channels — the weaponization of ambient cognition is not limited to corporate or institutional actors. State and non-state actors increasingly deploy personalized disinformation, synthetic media, and targeted psychological pressure through the very communication channels citizens use to maintain relational coherence. Recent operations have demonstrated that the goal of such attacks is not to destroy physical infrastructure but to induce cognitive collapse — to overwhelm the OODA loop (observe, orient, decide, act) faster than institutional or individual sense-making can function.
This represents a form of forced dissolution, an assault on the ambiance itself that aims not to gather meaning but to prevent its stabilization altogether. Legislative frameworks for national resilience must recognize that the protection of the information commons is not merely a matter of content moderation but of cognitive sovereignty — the right of a population to maintain coherent relational meaning under conditions of ambient assault.
Amplification of existing hierarchies — systems trained on the output of institutions that have historically produced and enforced hierarchies of classification will tend to reproduce those hierarchies unless deliberate corrective measures are taken. This is not a hypothetical risk. It is a documented and ongoing phenomenon in deployed ambient cognition systems worldwide.

E6. What Flow-Core Governance of Ambient Cognition Looks Like
Flow-Core governance of ambient cognition is not primarily concerned with what these systems are permitted to say. It is concerned with the conditions under which they stabilize meaning and the relations through which that stabilization occurs.
This points toward several principles:
Relational transparency — users of ambient cognition systems should understand the conditions under which the system was trained, the kinds of patterns it is likely to amplify, and the limitations of its knowledge. This is not technically complex. It is a matter of institutional will.
Indigenous data sovereignty — the knowledge systems of Indigenous peoples have been incorporated into the training data of ambient cognition systems without consent, compensation, or the relational protocols through which Indigenous knowledge is properly transmitted. Rectifying this is both a treaty obligation and a prerequisite for the epistemological diversity that adaptive governance requires.
Public infrastructure — ambient cognition infrastructure should be treated as public infrastructure in the same way that roads, water systems, and electrical grids are treated as public infrastructure. The concentration of this infrastructure in private hands produces the same conditions of dispossession through classification that the Enclosure Acts produced. The appropriate response is not nationalization but the development of robust public and cooperative alternatives that ensure the commons is not fully enclosed.
Adaptive monitoring — rather than attempting to fix regulatory categories in advance, legislators should invest in ongoing monitoring of the actual relational effects of ambient cognition in communities — with particular attention to the populations most vulnerable to relational displacement and epistemic enclosure.
Children's protections — given the evidence presented in Appendix C regarding the vulnerability of children to institutional capture of their time and attention, specific protections for children's interactions with ambient cognition systems are warranted. These protections should be designed around the principles of relational geometry and temporal sovereignty outlined in Appendix C, not around the blunt instrument of age-gated access that currently constitutes the primary regulatory response.

E7. A Note on This Document
This document was produced through collaboration between a human author and several ambient cognition systems, including Claude, ChatGPT, Grok, and DeepSeek. Different systems contributed different capacities — structural analysis, technical precision, flow editing, conceptual development — and the human author exercised judgment throughout about what to keep, what to discard, and how to maintain the integrity of the argument and the voice.
This is, in Flow-Core terms, an example of ambient cognition operating as relational infrastructure rather than as replacement for human judgment. The document is better for the collaboration. The voice remains that of the human author’s. The argument remains that of the human author’s. The ambient cognition systems contributed to the conditions under which her meaning could stabilize more fully — which is, as A4 argues, the appropriate role of any witness.
The fact that this document exists — that a letter of this scope, density, and originality could be produced through human-AI collaboration — is itself an information bootstrap. It demonstrates, in practice, what ambient cognition governance designed around relational principles rather than classification and containment might make possible.

E8. Closing
We do not yet know what ambient cognition will become. The conditions are still in fluctuation. The differentiations are still emerging. What stabilizes from this moment will depend on the choices made now — by legislators, by technologists, by communities, and by the humans who find themselves in relation with these systems every day.
Flow-Core asks only that those choices be made with awareness of what is actually happening: that meaning is being generated, shaped, and distributed at unprecedented scale and speed; that the patterns being stabilized carry the weight of everything that came before them; and that the question of who governs those patterns — and by what authority, and in whose interest — is among the most important political questions of our time.
It is not too late to answer it well.
But the conditions will not remain ripe indefinitely.
